{"cursor":"3536","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox person\n| image = caption = birth_date = birth_place = Wolverhampton, Staffordshire,\n| England death_date = death_place = Dunedin, New Zealand nationality =\n| birth_name = Rudall Charles Victor Hayward spouse = Hilda Maud\n| Moren (1923–1943) Patricia Rongomaitara Te Miha, aka Patricia\n| Miller (1943–1974) children = occupation = Film director, film\n| producer notable_works = The amazing dolphin of Opononi (1956), To love a\n| Maori (1972 influences = John Ford, D.W. Griffith, Raymond Longford influenced\n| = education = Wanganui Collegiate School (1916/17) Waihi School of Mines\n| alma_mater = religion = networth = years_active = 1920–1972\n}}\n\n\n'Rudall Charles Victor Hayward' (1900â1974) was a pioneer New Zealand filmmaker\nfrom the 1920s to the 1970s, who directed seven feature films and numerous\nothers. He was born in Wolverhampton, England, and died in Dunedin while\npromoting his last film.\n\nHe was the son of Rudall and Adelina Heyward, who came to New Zealand in 1905.\nWith Henry John Hayward (1866â1945) Rudall seniorâs brother, his parents were\ninvolved with entertainment and silent cinema in New Zealand, in Westâs Pictures\nand The Brescians.\n\nRudall (junior) was educated at Wanganui Collegiate School and the Waihi School\nof Mines. He worked in Australia c1920 under Raymond Longford (who in 1915-16\nwas filming in New Zealand), on some of Longford's films: \"The Sentimental\nBloke\", \"On Our Selection\", and \"Ruddâs New Selection\". He made his first two-\nreel comedy The Man from Freemanâs Bay in 1920 (which his uncle Henry offered\nhim Â£50 to burn!). His first feature was My Lady of the Cave (1922), then Rewiâs\nLast Stand (1925), The Te Kooti Trail (1927), and The Bush Cinderella (1928).\n\nIn 1928-30 he made 23 two-reel comedies with local settings and actors at\nvarious towns, and titles like: Tilly of Te Aroha, Hamiltonâs hectic husbands, A\n